ok, I think I found the problem here...

org.eclipse.jst.jsp.core.internal.util.DocumentProvider was already providing a custom entity resolver in order to avoid fetching of external dtds when validating is disabled, but the resolveEntity() method implementation is plain wrong!

looking at line 186 I can see:

public InputSource resolveEntity(String publicID, String systemID) throws SAXException, IOException {
	if (!isValidating())
		return null;

I think the intention here is to avoid fetching of external dtds returning a null: anyway, returning a null here simply makes the xml parser looking for the document "in the default way" by fetching it from the url. Returning null simply means that this entity resolver doesn't want to deal with this specific entity.

The fix here is simple, the correct way of totally skipping the loading of dtds is returning an "empty" input source, e.g:

 if (!isValidating())
    return new InputSource(new ByteArrayInputStream(new byte[0]));


I tested this patch locally on the project were I was experimenting performance problems and performance is greatly improved! Now loading of jsp files is 10x fast and no more unwanted connections are traced in the log.

For me this is a really *HOT* bug, can anybody test this patch or at least add the bug to the wtp hot list so that it will be considered before the next release?
